      {
        "content": "Social media companies routinely violate user privacy by collecting vast amounts of personal data without adequate consent or transparency. Users often unknowingly agree to invasive data collection practices through lengthy and complex terms of service that are rarely read or fully understood. This data is then utilized for targeted advertising, sold to third parties, or mishandled, as evidenced by numerous data breaches. Such practices not only exploit user privacy but also risk exposing sensitive information. Strict regulation is necessary to ensure that these companies prioritize data protection and uphold user rights, including clear consent mechanisms and the ability to control personal data.",
